    <activity>
        <introduction>
            <p>
                <alert>Work in Groups</alert>
            </p>
            <p>
                If you have a fence that is <m>30</m> meters long, what is the biggest garden you can build? Let's find out using a string!
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>What you need</alert>
            </p>
            <p>
                A piece of string exactly <m>30</m> cm long and a ruler.
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>What to do</alert>
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Form a rectangle with your string. Since the total length is <m>30</m> cm, the sum of one length and one width must be <m>15</m> cm.
                        </p>
                        <image width="50%">
                            <latex-image label="Rectangle with perimeter 30 cm">
                                \begin{tikzpicture}[x=1cm, y=1cm]

                                    % Rectangle
                                    \draw[thick, blue] (0,0) rectangle (9,6);

                                    % Length label (bottom)
                                    \draw[latex-latex, thick] (0,-0.7) -- (9,-0.7);
                                    \node[anchor=north] at (4.5,-0.7) {$l$ cm};

                                    % Width label (right)
                                    \draw[latex-latex, thick] (9.7,0) -- (9.7,6);
                                    \node[anchor=west] at (9.7,3) {$w$ cm};

                                    % Short tick marks on dimension lines
                                    \draw[thick] (0,-0.5) -- (0,-0.9);
                                    \draw[thick] (9,-0.5) -- (9,-0.9);
                                    \draw[thick] (9.5,0) -- (9.9,0);
                                    \draw[thick] (9.5,6) -- (9.9,6);

                                    % Constraint label inside rectangle
                                    \node[align=center, font=\large] at (4.5,3.5)
                                        {$l + w = 15$ cm};

                                    % Corner marks
                                    \draw (0.3,0) -- (0.3,0.3) -- (0,0.3);
                                    \draw (8.7,0) -- (8.7,0.3) -- (9,0.3);
                                    \draw (0.3,6) -- (0.3,5.7) -- (0,5.7);
                                    \draw (8.7,6) -- (8.7,5.7) -- (9,5.7);

                                \end{tikzpicture}
                            </latex-image>
                        </image>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            If we call the length <m>x</m>, the width is <m>15 - x</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Try different lengths and calculate the Area (<m>A = \text{length} \times \text{width}</m>):
                        </p>
                            <tabular border="minor" left="medium" right="medium" top="medium" bottom="medium">
                                <row header="yes">
                                    <cell>Length (<m>x</m>)</cell>
                                    <cell>Width (<m>15 - x</m>)</cell>
                                    <cell>Area (<m>x \times (15-x)</m>)</cell>
                                </row>
                                <row><cell>2 cm</cell><cell>13 cm</cell><cell>26 cm<m>^2</m></cell></row>
                                <row><cell>5 cm</cell><cell>10 cm</cell><cell>? cm<m>^2</m></cell></row>
                                <row><cell>7.5 cm</cell><cell>7.5 cm</cell><cell>? cm<m>^2</m></cell></row>
                                <row><cell>10 cm</cell><cell>5 cm</cell><cell>? cm<m>^2</m></cell></row>
                            </tabular>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Write the Area as a quadratic equation: <me>A = x(15 - x) = 15x - x^2</me>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Looking at your table, which length <m>x</m> gave the <alert>largest</alert> area? Is this shape a square?
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Use your equation to find the dimensions if the Area must be <m>54</m> cm<m>^2</m>. Solve <m>15x - x^2 = 54</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Share your work with your fellow learners.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
    </activity>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Structured Instruction</title>
        <p>
            <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To formalize the steps for modeling real-world problems with quadratic equations.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
        <paragraphs>
            <title>Key Takeaways &amp; Teacher Connection</title>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Connecting to Learner Work:</alert> Most physical problems resulting in quadratic equations will provide two mathematical solutions. Learners must be taught to evaluate these solutions against the constraints of reality (e.g., time and length cannot be negative).
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </paragraphs>
    </axiom>

    <insight>
        <p>
            Quadratic equations are essential for modeling various real-world phenomena where a variable depends on the square of another, or where two linear relationships are multiplied.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Common Applications:</alert>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p><alert>Projectile Motion:</alert> Calculating heights and distances for objects in flight.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p><alert>Area Problems:</alert> Finding dimensions of land or objects given area constraints.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p><alert>Business:</alert> Optimizing profit and revenue where price and demand are related.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p><alert>Engineering:</alert> Calculating resistance in circuits or the shape of reflectors.</p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Key Steps for Modeling:</alert>
            <ol>
                <li><p>Define the variable clearly.</p></li>
                <li><p>Set up the equation based on the given relationships.</p></li>
                <li><p>Solve using the most efficient method (Factoring, Quadratic Formula, completing the square, perfect square trinomials, etc.).</p></li>
                <li><p>Verify solutions by substituting the values back into the original equation.</p></li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </insight>

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/example-intro.ptx" />

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A ball is thrown from a height of <m>3</m> meters with an initial velocity of <m>14</m> m/s. Its height <m>h</m> at time <m>t</m> is given by <m>h = 3 + 14t - 5t^2</m>. When does the ball hit the ground?
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                The ball hits the ground when <m>h = 0</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>0 = 3 + 14t - 5t^2</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Rearrange to standard form: <m>5t^2 - 14t - 3 = 0</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                Using the quadratic formula: <m>a=5, b=-14, c=-3</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>t =\amp \frac{-(-14) \pm \sqrt{(-14)^2 - 4(5)(-3)}}{2(5)} </mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp \frac{14 \pm \sqrt{196 + 60}}{10} </mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp \frac{14 \pm \sqrt{256}}{10}</mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp \frac{14 \pm 16}{10}</mrow>
                </md>
                
            </p>
            <p>
                Solutions: <m>t = \frac{30}{10} = 3</m> or <m>t = \frac{-2}{10} = -0.2</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                Since time cannot be negative, the ball hits the ground after <m>3</m> seconds.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A rectangular steel frame has an external length of <m>10</m> cm and width of <m>8</m> cm. The metal has a uniform width of <m>x</m> cm. If the area of the metal is <m>28</m> cm<m>^2</m>, find the width <m>x</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                The area of the metal is the external area minus the internal area.
            </p>
            <p>
                External Area = <m>10 \times 8 = 80</m> cm<m>^2</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                Internal dimensions: Length = <m>10 - 2x</m>, Width = <m>8 - 2x</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                Internal Area = <m>(10 - 2x)(8 - 2x) = 80 - 20x - 16x + 4x^2 = 80 - 36x + 4x^2</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                Area of metal = <m>80 - (80 - 36x + 4x^2) = 36x - 4x^2</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                Given Area = <m>28</m>, so: <m>36x - 4x^2 = 28</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                Divide by 4: <me>9x - x^2 = 7 \implies x^2 - 9x + 7 = 0</me>.
            </p>
            <p>
                Using quadratic formula: <me>x = \frac{9 \pm \sqrt{81 - 28}}{2} = \frac{9 \pm \sqrt{53}}{2}</me>.
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>x = \frac{9 \pm 7.28}{2}</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>x = 8.14</m> or <m>x = 0.86</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                Since <m>x</m> cannot be greater than half the width (<m>4</m>), the width of the metal is approximately <m>0.86</m> cm.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A boat travels <m>15</m> km upstream and <m>15</m> km back downstream. The total time taken is <m>4</m> hours. If the speed of the current is <m>2</m> km/h, find the speed of the boat in still water.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Let the speed of the boat in still water be <m>v</m> km/h.
            </p>
            <p>
                Upstream speed = <m>v - 2</m>, Downstream speed = <m>v + 2</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                Time = <me>\frac{\text{Distance}}{\text{Speed}}</me>.
            </p>
            <p>
                Total Time: <me>\frac{15}{v-2} + \frac{15}{v+2} = 4</me>.
            </p>
            <p>
                Multiply by <m>(v-2)(v+2)</m>:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow> 15(v+2) + 15(v-2) =\amp 4(v^2 - 4) </mrow>
                    <mrow> 30v =\amp 4v^2 - 16 </mrow>
                    <mrow>4v^2-30v-16 =\amp 0</mrow>
                </md>
                
            </p>
            <p>
                Divide by 2: <m>2v^2 - 15v - 8 = 0</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                Factor: <m>(2v + 1)(v - 8) = 0</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>v = 8</m> or <m>v = -0.5</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                The speed of the boat is <m>8</m> km/h.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/assessment-intro.ptx" />

    <exercises>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    The length of a rectangular room is <m>3</m> meters more than its width. If the area of the room is <m>40</m> square meters, find the dimensions of the room.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    Let width be <m>w</m>. Length is <m>w+3</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <m>w(w+3) = 40 \implies w^2 + 3w - 40 = 0</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <m>(w+8)(w-5) = 0</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <m>w = 5</m> (width cannot be negative).
                </p>
                <p>
                    Width = <m>5</m> m, Length = <m>8</m> m.
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A company's profit <m>P</m> is given by <m>P = -x^2 + 40x - 300</m>, where <m>x</m> is the number of units sold. Find the number of units the company needs to sell to break even (i.e., when profit is zero).
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    The company breaks even at <m>10</m> units and <m>30</m> units.
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    The sum of the squares of two consecutive positive integers is <m>61</m>. Find the integers.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <!-- <p>
                    Let the integers be <m>n</m> and <m>n+1</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <m>n^2 + (n+1)^2 = 61</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <m>n^2 + n^2 + 2n + 1 = 61 \implies 2n^2 + 2n - 60 = 0</m>.
                </p> -->
                <!-- <p>
                    <m>n^2 + n - 30 = 0 \implies (n+6)(n-5) = 0</m>.
                </p> -->
                <p>
                    Since <m>n</m> is positive, <m>n=5</m>. The integers are <m>5</m> and <m>6</m>.
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A rectangular garden has a perimeter of <m>20</m> meters and an area of <m>24</m> square meters. Find the dimensions of the garden.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <!-- <p>
                    Let length be <m>L</m> and width be <m>W</m>. <m>2(L+W) = 20 \implies L+W = 10 \implies W = 10-L</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Area: <m>L(10-L) = 24 \implies 10L - L^2 = 24 \implies L^2 - 10L + 24 = 0</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Factoring: <m>(L-6)(L-4) = 0</m>.
                </p> -->
                <p>
                    Dimensions are <m>6</m> m by <m>4</m> m.
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    An object is launched from the ground with an initial velocity of <m>20</m> m/s. Its height <m>h</m> after <m>t</m> seconds is given by <m>h = 20t - 5t^2</m>. At what times is the object <m>15</m> meters high?
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <!-- <p>
                    Set <m>h = 15</m>: <m>15 = 20t - 5t^2 \implies 5t^2 - 20t + 15 = 0</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Divide by 5: <m>t^2 - 4t + 3 = 0</m>.
                </p> -->
                <p>
                    Factoring: <m>(t-1)(t-3) = 0</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    The object is <m>15</m> meters high at <m>1</m> second (going up) and <m>3</m> seconds (coming down).
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
    </exercises>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Differentiation</title>

        <table>
            <title>Differentiation Strategies</title>
            <tabular halign="left">
                <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
                    <cell>Learner Group</cell>
                    <cell>Strategy &amp; Learning Experience</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Struggling Learners (Support)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        Provide pre-drawn graphs of parabolas to help visualize roots and vertices. Focus on area problems with integer solutions.
                    </cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>On-Level Learners (Core)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <line>Complete the lesson activities and examples as described.</line>
                    </cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Advanced Learners (Challenge)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        Provide more complex problems involving speed-time or revenue optimization with non-integer roots. Ask them to derive the maximum height formula.
                    </cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </table>
    </axiom>

